{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608968"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16058"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16058"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0,0.19,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73888"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8749"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16058"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59364"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10627"},{"type":"tags","id":"10628"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20919"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73888"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe third stage of labour begins after the delivery of the baby and ends with the delivery of the placenta.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic of the third stage of labour?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Typically lasts 5-30 minutes","Begins with cervical effacement","Requires maternal pushing efforts throughout","Always requires manual removal of the placenta","Occurs before delivery of the baby"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethird stage of labour typically lasts 5-30 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E. It begins immediately after delivery of the baby and ends with delivery of the placenta. Signs that the placenta is separating include umbilical cord lengthening, a gush of blood, and the uterus becoming more globular and firm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical effacement\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during the first stage of labour\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal pushing efforts\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily associated with the second stage of labour\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManual removal of the placenta\u003C/strong\u003E is only required in cases of retained placenta\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe third stage occurs \u003Cstrong\u003Eafter delivery of the baby\u003C/strong\u003E, not before\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive management of the third stage with uterotonic medications reduces the risk of postpartum haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The third stage of labour involves placental separation and expulsion, typically lasting 5-30 minutes","Lengthening of the umbilical cord is a key sign of placental separation during the third stage","Active management of the third stage reduces the risk of postpartum haemorrhage"],"references":["Taebi M, Kalahroudi MA, Sadat Z, Saberi F. The duration of the third stage of labor and related factors. Iran J Nurs Midwifery Res. 2012 Feb;17(2 Suppl 1):S76-9. PMID: 23833605; PMCID: PMC3696975.","Labor S, Maguire S. The Pain of Labour. Rev Pain. 2008 Dec;2(2):15-9. doi: 10.1177/204946370800200205. PMID: 26526404; PMCID: PMC4589939","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59364"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16058"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59364"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T07:35:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T07:36:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8749"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73888"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api